x4freetext: Details of neutron spectrum.
Flight path to neutron detector 717.5+-0.2 cm.
Transmission. The data taking time per cycle for
the empty sample (3 cm thick Pb bremsstrahlung absorber
only) was 600 s, for the Au and Ta samples it was 900s.
The total measurement time was about 78 hours.
The order of the cycle was empty-Au-Ta-Pb in the first
half of the experiment, whereas it was
empty-Au-empty-Ta-empty-Pb in the second half with 300s
duration for empty.
The absolute scale of time of flight is determined
using the bremsstrahlung peak and known flight path.
The flight path has been verified by resonances with
strong elastic neutron scattering in 208Pb.
In the experiment 110 (130) measurements with Au (Ta)
were made and 320 with Pb absorber only.
Superconducting Electron Linac.
101.5625 kHz micropulse repetition rate.
Electrons are accelerated to 30 MeV .
The electrons generate bremsstrahlung photons which
release neutrons in secondary (gamma, n) reactions on
lead.
The energy range extends from about 10 keV to 10MeV .
The neutron source strength at the nominal beam current
was calculated with the Monte Carlo N-Particle
Transport Code MCNP-4C3 to be 10**13 neutrons/s .
The bunch duration is about 5 ps.
The transmitted neutrons were detected using a
plastic scintillator (Eljen EJ-200, 1000mm x 42mm x
11mm) that was read out on both ends using high-gain
Hamamatsu R2059-01 photomultiplier tubes (PMT).
Surrounded by a 1 cm thick lead shield.
The detection threshold for recoil protons about 10keV.
Detector count rate of about 10 kHz (empty sample beam)
corresponds to a neutron count rate of about 250 n/s.
On average, only every tenth accelerator bunch is
registered by the scintillator.
The time of flight of the transmitted neutrons was
measured in list mode with the Multi-Branch-System
(MBS1) real-time data acquisition developed at GSI
- with dispersion of 97.6 ps/channel.
Tantalum of natural isotopic composition (99.95%
purity) and 197Au (99.99% purity).
Each sample was combined with a 3 cm thick Pb absorber
to reduce the bremsstrahlung count rate. All Pb
absorbers and the Pb sample (diameter 25.0+-0.1mm,
length 30.0+-0.1mm) were made from a technical
lead alloy (PbSb(4) ). The data from the Pb sample were
used to determine the energy resolution of TOF
measurement.
Ta               Au
Standard density,g/cm3  16.65           19.32
Purity,weight %         99.95           99.99
The density was calculated from the measured dimensions
and mass of the sample to show agreement with the
standard density within the relative uncertainty of
6.E-3 or better. The Ta corresponds to ASTM B365 Grade
RO5200, the gold to standard fine gold.
Correction for a time-of-flight dependent dead time.
Subtraction of a constant random background in the
time-of-flight spectra:
- usual room background,
- background related to spurious neutron pulses,
- background related to neutrons scattered in the
collimator or in air and detected in the scintillator.
Neutron beam intensity fluctuations.
In-scattering of neutrons -the correction for multiple
in-scattering of fast neutrons in the Au and Ta samples
has been calculated to be negligibly small (< 0.1%)
using cross sections from the JEFF 3.1.1.
Resonant self-shielding in thick transmission samples:
-important correction at low neutron energy,
-above 100keV neutron energy is found to be negligible.
Of authors.
- This work is supported by the German Federal
Ministry for Education and Science (TRAKULA project,
contract # 02NUK13A) and by the European Commission in
the projects EFNUDAT (FP6-036434) and ERINDA
- Data of Fig.6 of J,EPJ/A,49,137,2013 :
The data from the Pb sample have been used to
determine the energy resolution of the time-of-flight
measurement, as discussed in sect. 4.6. The data are
not meant to be used for elemental neutron total cross
sections as the elemental composition of the absorber
sample ( PbSb4 absorber ) is not known with high
precision.

Statistical uncertainty was determined from
data rebinned to time-of-flight intervals of about
3.9 ns (bin size):
Energy resolution (source + detector):
Total systematic uncertainty 1.1% includes:
Random background subtraction 0.2%
Transmission normalization 0.5%
Areal density of the target sample 0.6%
Dead-time correction factor 0.8% .
The in-scattering and resonant self-absorption are
expected to be negligibly small in this measurement.
